# Slice 3.1b: Per-Process TTBR0s + 8-bit ASIDs + PF Diagnostic

> **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use `superpowers:subagent-driven-development`
> (recommended) or `superpowers:executing-plans` to implement this plan task-by-task.

**Goal:** Give each EL0 stub (A, B, C) its own page-table tree built from the
slice-3.1a frame allocator + `AddrSpace` API, swap `TTBR0_EL1` (ASID-tagged) on
every EL1 → EL0 transition, and trade `el0_sync_unexpected`'s generic panic on
EC=0x20/0x24 for a useful ESR/FAR/ELR decoder so slice 3.2's real page-fault
handler has a tractable diagnostic scaffold.

**Architecture:** Each stub's address space is fully owned (no static `L0_TABLE`
etc.). Code/stack frames are allocated from the slice-3.1a frame allocator,
populated via HHDM, and installed via `AddrSpace::map_page` from slice 3.1a.
TTBR0 is owned per-proc (`Proc::ttbr0_pa`, `Proc::asid`); kernel owns TTBR1
untouched. Context switch lives in `proc::sched::schedule_next` — one Rust
function, runs before `flush_deliver_msg` so the kernel can write to user
memory under the new proc's TTBR0. IPC user-copy stays single-AS in 3.1b
(caller's TTBR0 is live during SVC); cross-AS rewrite lands in 3.4.

**Tech Stack:** Rust `no_std` kernel, `cc`-crate assembly, aarch64
(`aarch64-unknown-none`), QEMU `virt` cortex-a72, Limine v9.x.

---

## Context

Phase 2 (slices 2.1–2.6) and slice 3.1a delivered a working microkernel with
IPC + scheduling + kernel-call dispatch and a frame allocator + addrspace API.
Today three EL0 stubs (A/B/C in `kernel/src/arch/aarch64/userland.rs`) all
share one hand-rolled TTBR0 backed by five static `.bss` page-table arrays
(`L0_TABLE`, `L1_TABLE`, `L2_TABLE`, `L3_CODE_TABLE`, `L3_STACK_TABLE`) and
six static `UserPage`s for code/stack. Any EL0 translation fault hits
`el0_sync_unexpected` and panics with `EC=…`.

Slice 3.1b transitions to true per-process address isolation: each stub gets
its own `AddrSpace` (slice 3.1a) with freshly allocated code/stack frames
copied from kernel-image stub blobs via HHDM, an 8-bit ASID assigned by a new
allocator, and a per-context-switch `MSR TTBR0_EL1` + `TLBI ASIDE1` sequence.
Slice 3.1b also replaces the EC=0x20 / EC=0x24 panic with a one-page decoder
(FSC + WnR + ISV) so slice 3.2's real `do_page_fault` lands on top of useful
diagnostics. IPC user-copy semantics are unchanged in 3.1b — the SVC handler
runs in the caller's TTBR0, so single-AS reads still walk the active page
tables. The phase-3.4 cross-AS HHDM-walk redesign of `flush_deliver_msg` is
out of scope here.

**Pre-flight (one-time):** PR slice 3.1a first, merge into `main`, then
checkout `main` locally and `git pull`. Slice 3.1b branches off the fresh
`main`, in-place (no worktree).

---

## File Map

